<BlogPost
  title="Getting Started with Pikos"
  description="A quick look at what happens when you open Pikos for the first time."
  date="2026-04-07"
>

  <p>
    You download Pikos, open it, and you're in. No account creation, no onboarding wizard, no email verification. The app opens and you're looking at your workspace.
  </p>

  <h2>Create your first page</h2>

  <p>
    Press <code>Cmd+N</code> and a small dialog appears. Type a title — "Grocery list" or "Project ideas" or "Monday standup notes" — and hit Enter. That's a page. It shows up in your sidebar and the editor opens on the right.
  </p>

  <p>
    Start typing. The editor supports rich text — bold, headings, bullet lists, checklists, code blocks. If you know Markdown, you can type it directly and it converts as you go. If you don't, there's a formatting toolbar that appears when you select text.
  </p>

  <h2>Turn it into a task</h2>

  <p>
    Click the status indicator at the top of the page and set it to "In Progress." Now it's a task. Set a priority if you want — Urgent, High, Medium, Low — or leave it blank. Add tags to group related pages together.
  </p>

  <p>
    None of this is required. A page with no status, no priority, and no tags is just a note. Add structure when it's useful, skip it when it's not.
  </p>

  <h2>Schedule it</h2>

  <p>
    Click the date field and pick a day and time. Now your page is a calendar event too. Toggle the calendar panel open with <code>Cmd+Shift+C</code> and you'll see it on your week view. Drag it to a different time slot to reschedule.
  </p>

  <h2>Organize with folders</h2>

  <p>
    Right-click in the sidebar to create a folder. Drag pages into it, or use the context menu to move them. Folders can have custom colors so you can tell them apart at a glance.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two built-in views are always there: <strong>Today</strong> shows everything scheduled for today plus anything overdue. <strong>Inbox</strong> shows pages that aren't in any folder yet — a catch-all for quick captures you haven't organized.
  </p>

  <h2>Quick capture</h2>

  <p>
    The fastest way to get something into Pikos: press <code>Cmd+N</code> and type naturally. "Call dentist tomorrow high priority #health" creates a page titled "Call dentist," schedules it for tomorrow, sets priority to high, and tags it "health." The parser does its best to extract structure from plain text so you don't have to click through menus.
  </p>

  <h2>Search everything</h2>

  <p>
    Press <code>Cmd+K</code> to open search. It's full-text — it searches inside your pages, not just titles. Results are ranked by relevance, with title matches weighted higher. Each result shows a content preview so you can find the right page without opening every match.
  </p>

  <h2>That's the basics</h2>

  <p>
    Pikos doesn't have a learning curve so much as a discovery curve. The core actions — create a page, write in it, schedule it, organize it — work the way you'd expect. The rest (keyboard shortcuts, sort modes, export options) is there when you want it and invisible when you don't.
  </p>

</BlogPost>
